This section of the YAML represents the absolute core mechanics of the Sidecar Design Pattern.

Let's dissect how this specific block of code binds these two radically different containers into a single, cohesive unit inside the same Pod, focusing on how they share storage and execute tasks.

1. The Shared Volume Mappings
The defining characteristic of this setup is that both containers reference the exact same volume name (shared-logs), but they interact with it independently.

                  [ Pod: web-app-with-sidecar ]
  ┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │                                                          │
  │   ┌───────────────────┐          ┌───────────────────┐   │
  │   │   main-web-app    │          │log-shipper-sidecar│   │
  │   │     (nginx)       │          │     (alpine)      │   │
  │   └─────────┬─────────┘          └─────────┬─────────┘   │
  │             │                              │             │
  │  mounts to: /var/log/nginx    mounts to: /var/log/nginx  │
  │             │                              │             │
  │             └──────────────┬───────────────┘             │
  │                            ▼                             │
  │                 ┌────────────────────┐                   │
  │                 │    shared-logs     │                   │
  │                 │    (emptyDir)      │                   │
  │                 └────────────────────┘                   │
  └──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
main-web-app: Nginx is compiled by default to output its log stream directly to a physical file located at /var/log/nginx/access.log. By mapping shared-logs to /var/log/nginx, you are hijacking that local folder. Nginx thinks it is writing to regular container storage, but it is actually streaming data straight onto the shared host disk space.

